  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A passed-in result at auction is more common than many sellers expect, and it is not automatically the beginning of a long, difficult campaign. What it means, and what it leads to, depends almost entirely on what the auction revealed and how your agent responds in the minutes and hours after the gavel comes down without a sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What passing in actually means</h2>
      <p>Passing in means the auction concluded without bidding reaching your reserve price, and the property did not sell under the hammer. The auctioneer declared the property passed in, and the sale now moves off auction terms and into private negotiation or private treaty.</p>

      <p>It is worth separating two different scenarios. In the first, there were registered bidders who bid but stopped short of your reserve. In the second, there were no bids at all or only a vendor bid. The post-auction path and the interpretation of what happened are different in each case.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The immediate post-auction window</h2>
      <p>If there was a highest bidder, they have the first right to negotiate with you privately after the auction. This is not a legal right that persists indefinitely: it is a procedural courtesy that your agent should act on immediately. The moment the auction ends, your agent should move the highest bidder and their representative into a private space, away from the crowd, and begin a direct negotiation.</p>

      <p>The window is short. The buyer is still emotionally engaged in the property and has already committed to a price in public. That commitment is a negotiating asset. As time passes, the buyer's resolve can fade, their partner can second-guess the number, and the sense of occasion that drives auction outcomes dissipates. A good agent treats the thirty minutes after a pass-in as almost as important as the auction itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to approach the negotiation</h2>
      <p>You are not obligated to accept any offer after a pass-in. The reserve was set for a reason, and the buyer knows the property did not sell. But the auction data is real. If the highest bid was close to your reserve, within 3% to 5%, a relatively small movement from one or both sides can close the deal and avoid the cost and delay of relisting under private treaty.</p>

      <p>The approach that produces the best outcomes in this situation is a direct conversation between your agent and the buyer, guided by the actual auction data. How many registered bidders were there? Did they stop at a round number that suggests they had room to move? What did they say to the agent during the campaign about their limit? Your agent should be using all of that intelligence in this negotiation, not just repeating the reserve number.</p>

      <p>If the highest bid was significantly below your reserve, by 10% or more, that is a different conversation. At that gap, you are not closing a negotiation: you are reassessing whether the reserve reflects current market appetite. That reassessment needs to happen with clear eyes, not defensiveness.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Reading the auction result as market data</h2>
      <p>Whether or not you negotiate to a contract on auction day, the auction generated data you did not have before. How many groups registered? How many bid? At what point did bidding stop? What was the highest bidder's read on the property? These are not just emotional responses: they are precise signals about what the current market thinks your property is worth.</p>

      <p>A result where three buyers registered and two bid to within 5% of reserve tells you something very different from one where one buyer registered and made a single low bid. In the first case, you have genuine competition and a price that the market is approaching. In the second, you may have a pricing or marketing problem that the private treaty campaign needs to address.</p>

      <p>The enquiry numbers and inspection counts from the campaign also matter here. If you had forty online enquiries, fifteen groups through open homes, and three registered bidders, the funnel was working. If you had forty enquiries and three inspections, something deterred buyers from attending, and that needs to be investigated before relisting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Moving to private treaty after the auction</h2>
      <p>If the post-auction negotiation does not produce a contract on the day, the property typically transitions to a private treaty campaign within 24 hours. Most Brisbane agents move quickly on this because a passed-in property that sits dormant for a week looks like a problem property. The relisting should have a clear price and a plan.</p>

      <p>Private treaty after a pass-in works best when the agent contacts every buyer who inspected during the auction campaign immediately. These buyers have already done their due diligence and know the property. They are the warm pipeline. A well-run post-auction private treaty campaign targets them first, before the listing is back on the portals and before the broader market can form a 'failed at auction' narrative.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The reserve question</h2>
      <p>Whether to reduce the reserve after a pass-in is a conversation between you and your agent based on the campaign data. It is not a decision that should be made defensively or emotionally in the hours after the auction. Take the data: enquiry numbers, inspection counts, number of registered bidders, highest bid, buyer feedback from your agent. Ask your agent to explain exactly what the numbers tell them and what they would recommend for the private treaty price guide.</p>

      <p>If the honest read is that the reserve was set above current market conditions, adjusting it is not a concession: it is an accurate response to real evidence. Holding firm on a reserve that the market has rejected once does not make the property more valuable. It makes the campaign longer and the eventual outcome lower.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing the perception reset</h2>
      <p>A passed-in property carries a perception risk in the Brisbane market. Buyers who were not at the auction will see it back on the portals and may assume it did not sell because something was wrong with it. This perception is not always accurate, but it is real, and it needs to be addressed in the re-launch strategy.</p>

      <p>The most effective way to reset buyer perception is to move quickly, communicate clearly, and price accurately. A property that is back on the market within 48 hours with a credible private treaty price and a direct message to all inspecting buyers from the auction campaign is in a far stronger position than one that drifts back online a week later with no explanation and the same price guide it had before the auction.</p>

      <p>Your agent's response in the first 48 hours after a pass-in is one of the clearest signals of how capable they are. The agents who manage this period well are the ones worth having when things do not go to plan.</p>

